M|Tran|tx|Startups sometimes need to transition from one engine to another as they mature.
M|Comm|tx|\| From \| To \| Trigger \| Example \|
M|Comm|tx|\|------\|-----\|---------\|---------\|
M|Comm|tx|\| Viral \| Paid \| Viral coefficient plateaus; need predictable growth \| Instagram (viral) adding paid ad capability for businesses \|
M|Comm|tx|\| Paid \| Sticky \| CAC rising; retention more efficient than acquisition \| SaaS companies shifting budget from ad to cs sc \|
M|Comm|tx|\| Sticky \| Viral \| Strong retention base ready to amplify through sharing \| Slack moving from sticky (enterprise adoption) to viral (team invites) \|
M|Comm|tx|\| Paid \| Viral \| Unit economics prove pd works; now seeking organic scale \| Dropbox reducing ad spend after referral program scaled \|
M|Tran|it|[ ] Current engine is well-understood and optimized (you are not fleeing a broken engine)
M|Tran|it|[ ] The new engine has initial evidence of working (not just theory)
M|Tran|it|[ ] Metrics and dashboards are set up for the new engine
M|Tran|it|[ ] Team capabilities align w/ the new engine (virality needs pd skills; paid needs mk skills)
M|Tran|it|[ ] Budget and timeline are allocated for the transition period
M|Tran|it|[ ] Fallback plan exists if the new engine does not deliver within the expected timeframe
M|Tran|tx|The engine of growth is not a mk st; it is a pd st. The most effective growth comes from building the engine into the pd itself, not bolting it on after launch.